security.cfg — kernel security policy

LOCATION
  /etc/security.cfg

FORMAT
  return {
    enforce      = true | false,
    default_user = "<name>",
  }

DESCRIPTION
  enforce  controls whether cap.check actually denies on a missing
           capability. With enforce=false the kernel logs every denial
           to the audit log but lets the call proceed; this is the
           "log-only" mode used during initial bring-up of a fresh
           machine. The shipped default is true.

  default_user is informational; sessiond uses it as the username
           offered at the login prompt.

  Capability enforcement bites at every:
    * exec.exec      → syscall:exec
    * vfs.open(W)    → syscall:write:<path>
    * proc.kill      → syscall:kill[:9]
    * drv.data       → component:data

  An empty /etc/passwd causes sessiond to spawn a root shell with
  caps={"*"} regardless of enforce — the bootstrap path stays
  reachable on first boot.

SEE ALSO
  useradd(1), sudo(1), audit(1), passwd(5)
